        "text": "Cartography, the art and science of graphically representing a geographical area, has a rich and complex history that reflects human intellectual progress. The earliest known maps were not of the Earth, but of the heavens. Dots found in the caves of Lascaux, dating back to approximately 16,500 BCE, depict parts of the night sky, including constellations like the Pleiades. For early humans, mapping was a means of visualising their relationship with the cosmos rather than navigate terrain. As civilisations developed, the focus shifted to land. In ancient Babylon, clay tablets were used to plot fields, roads, and cities. The Babylonian Map of the World, created in the 6th century BCE, is widely considered the oldest surviving map of the world, presenting a symbolic, mythological view of the known earth surrounded by a bitter river.\n\nIt was during the Hellenistic period that cartography began to merge with scientific principles. Ancient Greek scholars made significant breakthroughs in understanding the Earth's true shape and size. Eratosthenes of Cyrene, writing in the 3rd century BCE, calculated the Earth's circumference with remarkable accuracy using simple geometry and the shadows of the sun. He is credited with coining the term 'geography' and establishing the first grid system of latitude and longitude. Later, in the 2nd century CE, Claudius Ptolemy published his monumental work, Geographia. Ptolemy revolutionized mapmaking by introducing a systematic method of projection to represent a spherical Earth on a flat surface, establishing coordinates for thousands of locations throughout the Roman Empire. Although Ptolemy's maps contained considerable errors—most notably underestimating the size of the oceans—his principles laid the foundation for modern geography.\n\nDuring the Middle Ages, European cartography took a step back from scientific accuracy, focusing instead on religious symbolism. This era was dominated by the 'T and O' maps, which depicted the world as a flat disc divided into three continents—Asia, Europe, and Africa—by a T-shaped water body representing the Mediterranean, the Nile, and the Don. These maps placed Jerusalem at the very centre of the world, serving a theological purpose rather than a practical one. In contrast, the Islamic world preserved and expanded upon Ptolemaic knowledge. Cartographers like Muhammad al-Idrisi produced highly detailed and accurate maps for travel and trade, culminating in the Tabula Rogeriana in 1154, which was the most advanced world map of its time.\n\nThe Age of Discovery in the 15th and 16th centuries generated an urgent demand for functional sea charts. As European explorers ventured across unknown oceans, the limitations of traditional map projections became a critical hazard. Navigators required maps that preserved constant bearings. In 1569, Flemish cartographer Gerardus Mercator resolved this challenge by introducing his famous projection. Mercator's projection allowed navigators to plot a straight line on a map that corresponded to a constant compass direction, though it distorted the size of landmasses near the poles. Despite these distortions, it became the standard for nautical navigation, cementing cartography's role in global trade and exploration.",
