        "text": "Mesopotamia, the fertile valley between the Tigris and Euphrates rivers, is often referred to as the cradle of civilisation. In this region, early human groups transitioned from foraging to settled farming, establishing some of the world's earliest cities. The primary catalyst for this shift was the development of highly sophisticated agricultural techniques. However, farming in Mesopotamia was far from straightforward. The region faced extreme weather conditions, characterised by scorching summer heat and unpredictable, violent spring floods. Since the flooding of the Tigris and Euphrates did not align with the crop growing season, farmers could not rely on natural rainfall or flooding to sustain their fields.\n\nTo overcome these environmental hurdles, the Mesopotamians constructed an elaborate network of canals, dykes, and reservoirs. This irrigation system allowed farmers to channel river water directly to their fields when it was most needed, transforming arid plains into highly productive land. The construction and maintenance of these systems required a high degree of communal organisation and central authority, which in turn spurred the development of complex social structures. Government officials managed the distribution of water, ensuring that all fields received adequate supply while preventing disputes among landholders. The surplus grain generated by this irrigated agriculture supported a growing population of non-farmers, including priests, artisans, and administrators.\n\nThe primary staple crop of ancient Mesopotamia was barley. Barley was preferred over wheat because of its higher tolerance to saline soil, which became an increasingly severe issue due to continuous irrigation. Under the intense heat, water evaporated rapidly from the soil surface, leaving behind salt minerals that slowly poisoned the land. Alongside barley, Mesopotamians cultivated dates, sesame, lentils, and peas, and raised livestock such as sheep, goats, and cattle. The date palm was particularly valued, as it provided not only food but also timber, fibers, and shade for smaller crops growing underneath.\n\nTechnological innovations further enhanced agricultural productivity. The invention of the seed plough around the 4th millennium BCE revolutionized the planting process. Unlike simple scratch ploughs, this advanced tool featured a funnel that allowed seeds to be dropped directly into the furrow as the earth was turned. This reduced the amount of seed wasted and saved considerable labor. Despite these achievements, Mesopotamian agriculture was ultimately vulnerable to ecological decline. Over time, the build-up of salt in the soil led to a significant drop in crop yields, forcing farmers to abandon once-fertile fields and contributing to the political instability of the region's city-states.",
