        "title": "Kepler and the Search for Exoplanets",
        "text": "For centuries, humanity has looked up at the night stars and wondered if we are alone in the vast universe. The answer to this age-old question began to take shape with the launch of NASA's Kepler Space Telescope in 2009. Kepler's primary scientific mission was to survey a portion of our region of the Milky Way galaxy to discover Earth-sized exoplanets—planets outside our solar system—orbiting other stars, particularly those in or near the habitable zone. The habitable zone, often colloquially called the Goldilocks zone, is the region around a star where temperatures are just right for liquid water to exist on a planet's surface, a key ingredient for life as we know it.\n\nKepler detected these distant exoplanets using a technique known as the transit method. This scientific technique involves monitoring the brightness of thousands of stars simultaneously. When a planet passes, or transits, in front of its host star from Kepler's point of view, it blocks a tiny fraction of the star's light. By measuring this periodic, minute dip in brightness, astronomers can confirm the planet's existence, calculate its orbital period, and estimate its actual physical size. A larger planet blocks more light, resulting in a deeper dip, while a planet farther from its star has a longer orbital period.\n\nAlthough the transit method is highly effective, it has distinct limitations. It only works if the planet's orbit is aligned precisely along Kepler's line of sight. If the orbit is tilted even slightly, the planet will never pass in front of the star from our perspective, and the transit will go undetected. To confirm these candidates, astronomers often rely on ground-based telescopes using the radial velocity method, which measures the gravitational tug a planet exerts on its host star, causing the star to wobble slightly. This complementary technique helps rule out false positives.\n\nDespite these challenges, Kepler was immensely successful. Over its nine-year mission, it monitored over 150,000 stars and confirmed the existence of more than 2,600 exoplanets. Perhaps its most significant scientific contribution was showing that planets are common throughout the galaxy. Kepler's data suggested that between 20 to 50 percent of stars visible in the night sky are likely to have small, possibly rocky planets in their habitable zones. Kepler was retired in 2018 after running out of fuel, but its legacy continues to shape the field of astrobiology and modern space exploration.",
