        "passage_number": 3,
        "title": "The Paradox of Choice: How Too Many Options Hurt Us",
        "text": "In a seminal experiment conducted at a gourmet food store, psychologists Sheena Iyengar and Mark Lepper set up a display of jam samples. On some days they offered 24 varieties; on others, just 6. The table with 24 options attracted more attention, but the one with 6 options was far more effective at converting browsers into buyers—a rate roughly ten times higher. This study, now iconic in the field of behavioral economics, helped crystallize a counter-intuitive idea: more choice does not necessarily lead to more satisfaction or better decisions. In fact, it can lead to paralysis, regret, and unhappiness.\n\nPsychologist Barry Schwartz, who coined the term 'paradox of choice,' argues that while some choice is undeniably better than none, an excess of options creates several psychological burdens. The first is decision paralysis. When faced with many alternatives, the cognitive effort required to evaluate each option can become so overwhelming that individuals avoid making a decision altogether, or else defer it indefinitely. This phenomenon has been observed in consumer markets, retirement plan selection, and even medical treatment choices. In one study, employees were significantly less likely to enroll in a 401(k) retirement plan when offered ten or more investment options compared to when offered only two.\n\nEven when a decision is successfully made, excessive choice can diminish satisfaction through two related mechanisms: opportunity cost and regret. With many options available, the alternatives not chosen loom larger in the mind. The more enticing these foregone options seem, the more a person may second-guess their decision, feeling that the chosen option falls short relative to the alternatives. This anticipation of regret can be paralyzing, and the actual experience of regret after making a choice can undermine satisfaction with even an objectively good outcome. Furthermore, excessive choice tends to shift blame inward. When there are few choices, a bad outcome can be blamed on circumstance. When there are many, a person is more likely to feel personally responsible for any failure to choose optimally.\n\nSchwartz distinguishes between two types of decision-makers: 'maximizers,' who feel compelled to make the objectively best choice by exhaustively analyzing all options, and 'satisficers,' who set criteria and choose the first option that meets them. While maximizers tend to make objectively better choices, research shows they are consistently less satisfied with their decisions and more prone to depression and regret. Satisficers, by contrast, tend to experience greater well-being despite sometimes settling for a 'good enough' option. The path to greater happiness, Schwartz suggests, lies not in having unlimited choice, but in learning to impose voluntary constraints on the options we consider.",
