        "title": "The Economics of Happiness",
        "text": "For much of the twentieth century, economists largely assumed that income and happiness were synonymous: as a nation's economy grew and individual wealth increased, so too would the well-being of its citizens. This assumption, enshrined in the pursuit of GDP growth as the paramount measure of national progress, has been increasingly challenged by decades of psychological and economic research into the nature of subjective well-being.\n\nThe most provocative finding in this field is known as the Easterlin Paradox, named after economist Richard Easterlin who published his findings in 1974. Easterlin's research showed that within a given country, wealthier individuals report higher life satisfaction—consistent with the intuitive link between money and happiness. However, when comparing countries across different income levels, richer nations do not consistently report significantly greater happiness than poorer ones. Furthermore, as a country's average income has risen over time, average happiness levels have not correspondingly increased. The United States, for example, saw dramatic GDP growth over the second half of the twentieth century, yet reported life satisfaction showed little upward trend during the same period.\n\nSeveral psychological mechanisms have been proposed to explain this paradox. The first is hedonic adaptation: the well-documented tendency of people to return to a relatively stable level of happiness after major positive or negative life events. A lottery winner, research suggests, will be significantly happier in the first months after winning, but typically reverts to near their pre-winning happiness level within a year. Similarly, people adapt to improved living standards, taking for granted comforts that were once exciting luxuries. The second mechanism is social comparison. Humans are intensely social creatures who evaluate their status not in absolute terms but relative to those around them. An increase in income brings satisfaction only insofar as it improves one's relative standing; if everyone around you becomes equally wealthier, the gain in satisfaction is minimal.\n\nThese findings have significant policy implications. Bhutan famously pioneered the concept of Gross National Happiness (GNH) as an alternative metric of national progress, measuring factors such as psychological well-being, cultural preservation, environmental sustainability, and good governance. More recently, countries including New Zealand and Iceland have adopted 'Wellbeing Budgets,' prioritizing mental health, child poverty reduction, and environmental indicators alongside traditional economic metrics. These initiatives reflect a growing consensus among policymakers that GDP is a necessary but insufficient indicator of a nation's true health.",
