        "title": "Nanotechnology: The Science of the Very Small",
        "text": "Nanotechnology, the manipulation of matter at the atomic and molecular scale (typically defined as operating at scales between 1 and 100 nanometres), has evolved from a theoretical concept articulated by physicist Richard Feynman in his celebrated 1959 lecture 'There's Plenty of Room at the Bottom,' to a multi-billion-dollar industry touching nearly every sector of the modern economy. The prefix 'nano' derives from the Greek for 'dwarf,' and at this scale, the behaviour of materials deviates significantly from their properties at the macroscale due to quantum mechanical effects and the dominance of surface area relative to volume.\n\nMedicine represents one of the most transformative application areas for nanotechnology. Nanoparticle-based drug delivery systems promise to revolutionize cancer treatment by targeting tumors directly, reducing the severe side effects of conventional chemotherapy where drugs are distributed throughout the entire body. Iron oxide nanoparticles are being investigated for use in hyperthermia treatment of tumors—when exposed to an alternating magnetic field, they generate heat locally, destroying cancer cells while sparing surrounding healthy tissue. The mRNA vaccines developed during the COVID-19 pandemic relied on lipid nanoparticles to encapsulate and deliver fragile mRNA molecules into human cells, representing a landmark practical application of nanotechnology in medicine.\n\nIn materials science, nanotechnology has enabled the creation of materials with extraordinary properties. Carbon nanotubes—cylinders of carbon atoms with diameters in the nanometre range—are estimated to have a tensile strength over 100 times that of steel at a fraction of its weight. Graphene, a single layer of carbon atoms arranged in a hexagonal lattice, is the thinnest known material, yet it is also one of the strongest, with remarkable electrical conductivity that makes it a leading candidate for next-generation electronics. Self-healing materials, which can repair damage to their structure autonomously, are being developed by incorporating nanocapsules filled with a healing agent that ruptures upon structural damage.\n\nDespite its immense promise, nanotechnology raises significant ethical and safety concerns. The same properties that make nanoparticles useful—their small size and high reactivity—also make their interaction with biological systems unpredictable. Studies have raised concerns about the potential toxicity of certain nanoparticles if they accumulate in tissues or cross the blood-brain barrier. The environmental impact of nanomaterials, particularly regarding their persistence in ecosystems and potential effects on non-target organisms, remains poorly understood. Regulatory frameworks in most countries are still adapting to address materials that may be chemically identical to known, safe substances but behave in fundamentally different ways due to their scale.",
