        "title": "The Psychology of Colour",
        "text": "Colour is far more than a visual phenomenon; it is a powerful psychological force that profoundly shapes human perception, behaviour, and emotion. The study of colour psychology explores the associations, meanings, and physiological responses that colours evoke. While some responses to colour appear to be universal or near-universal—stemming from biological or evolutionary roots—many are deeply cultural, varying significantly across societies and historical periods.\n\nThe physiological effects of colour exposure are well-documented. Research has shown that certain colours can measurably alter heart rate, blood pressure, and even muscle response. Red, associated with warmth and danger across many cultures, has been shown in multiple studies to increase physiological arousal. A 2011 study found that athletes competing against opponents wearing red lose more often than when facing opponents in other colours, suggesting an unconscious threat response. Conversely, blue tones are associated with calmness and reduced physiological arousal. Blue-tinted lighting has been trialled on railway platforms in Japan with documented reductions in the number of suicide attempts, while several cities have reported reduced crime rates after installing blue streetlights.\n\nColour associations are, however, far from universally constant. White is associated with purity and weddings in Western cultures, but in several East Asian cultures, including China and Korea, white is the traditional colour of mourning. Similarly, green carries strong associations with nature, health, and environmental consciousness in the West, yet in some cultures it symbolises death or infidelity. The implications for global marketing are significant. A colour scheme chosen to evoke trust and reliability in one market may inadvertently signal danger or instability in another.\n\nIn designed environments, colour is a powerful tool. Hospital rooms painted in calming shades of green or blue have been shown to reduce patient anxiety and accelerate recovery. Research in educational settings has linked warm, stimulating colours in primary school classrooms to improved learning outcomes for younger children, while cooler, less saturated tones appear to benefit concentration in older students. The work of Faber Birren, a pioneering colour consultant in the mid-20th century, established the field of applied colour psychology, influencing the design of factories, offices, hospitals, and military environments to maximize productivity and well-being.",
